  "prompt": "How do they prove that light travels in wave?",
  "response": "The proof that light behaves as a wave came from several key experiments and observations in the history of physics:\n\n1. **Interference Patterns:**\n   - **Thomas Young's Double-Slit Experiment (1801):** Young's experiment showed that when light passes through two closely spaced slits, it creates an interference pattern of alternating bright and dark fringes on a screen. This pattern is characteristic of waves interfering with each other; if light were composed of particles, we would expect to see two distinct bands corresponding to the slits.\n   \n2. **Diffraction:** \n   - When light encounters an obstacle or a slit that is comparable in size to its wavelength, it bends around the edges and spreads out. This behavior can only be explained if light has wave properties.\n\n3. **Polarization:**\n   - Light waves can be polarized, meaning that they oscillate in a particular direction or plane. This behavior is typical of transverse waves rather than particles.\n\n4. **Huygens' Principle:**\n   - Christiaan Huygens proposed that every point on a wavefront is a source of secondary spherical wavelets, and the sum of these wavelets forms the new wavefront. This principle helps in explaining reflection, refraction, and diffraction, phenomena observed with light.\n\n5. **Electromagnetic Theory:**\n   - James Clerk Maxwell's equations (constructed in the 1860s) describe light as an electromagnetic wave. Light is a transverse wave that propagates through the oscillation of electric and magnetic fields perpendicular to each other and to the direction of propagation.\n\n6. **Experimental Confirmation of Electromagnetic Waves:**\n   - Heinrich Hertz\u2019s experiments in 1887 demonstrated the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by Maxwell, validating that light itself is an electromagnetic wave.\n\nThese collectively support the wave theory of light.",
